\section{Trigonometric Integrals}
\label{sec:trig-integr}
As we've stated before, substitution is a powerful tool which
transforms a problem into a more recognizable problem.  Furthermore,
there is no such thing as a wrong substitution.  Rather the question
is if the substitution actually helps to simplify the problem.  You
may find it surprising to learn that sometimes introducing something
apparently complicated like a trigonometric function can actually
simplify the problem.  The following problem illustrates this.

\begin{embeddedproblem}{}
  Recall Problem~\label{prob:Tractrix}, where we examined the
  tractrix.  Specifically, we were interested in the path of the
  center of the rear axle of a trailer as the tractor pulls the front
  of the trailer up the $y-$axis. [See figure at the right for the top view.]
  Initially, the center of the rear axle of the tractor is at the
  origin and the center of the rear axle of the trailer is at the
  point $(1,0).$\\
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1in,width=2in]{../Figures/Tractrix}}

  In Problem $44,$ you showed that the path $y=y(x)$ that the center of
  the rear axle of the trailer follows (tractix) must satisfy the
  initial value problem (IVP)
  $$
  \dfdx{y}{x}=-\frac{\sqrt{1-x^2}}{x},\ \ \ y(1)=0.
  $$
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
  \item Find the equation $y=y(x)$ for the tractrix.  [Hint: After you
    separate the variables, you can substitute $x=\cos(\theta)$ in your
    integral.]  Graph your answer to see if it makes sense.
  \item How far will the tractor have gone (in trailer lengths) before
    the trailer is within one degree of vertical?
  \end{enumerate}
\end{embeddedproblem}

\begin{embeddedproblem}{}
  Recall Problem~\ref{prob:pursuit} where we considered the top view
  of a plane $P$ starting at the point $(1,0)$ and traveling up the line
  $x=1$ at a constant speed $v.$  When the plane is at $(1,0),$ a homing
  missile $M$ is fired from the origin directly at the plane. Assuming
  that the missile travels at a speed which is $k$ times the speed of
  the plane $(k>1)$ and is always aimed directly at the plane, we will
  find the path the missile takes.  The diagram below shows the
  situation at time.\\
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2in,width=2in]{../Figures/PursuitCurve}}
  If we let s denote the distance the missile has traveled at time
  $t,$ we showed in Problem~\ref{prob:pursuit} that the missile's path
  must satisfy the IVP
  $$
  \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{\frac{s}{k-y}}{1-x},\ \       y(0)=0.
  $$
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
  \item Use this to show that the missile's path must satisfy the IVP
    $$
    (1-x)\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{1}{k}\dfdx{s}{x}=\frac{1}{k} \sqrt{1+(dy/dx)^2 }
    $$
    with the initial conditions $y(0)=0,$
    $\left.\dfdx{y}{x}\right|_{x=0}=0.$
  \item Solve the IVP in part (a).  [Hint:  Let  $z=\dfdx{y}{x}$   and
    solve the resulting equations for $z.$]
  \item How long does it take for the missile to catch the plane?

  \end{enumerate}  
\end{embeddedproblem}

